{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638910"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:00:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17748"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17748"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.11,0,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10462"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60132"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6553"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"},{"type":"tags","id":"12288"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset severe abdominal pain and dizziness. He has a history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia. He does not take any regular medications. He appears pale and diaphoretic on examination. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure is 80/50 mmHg, respiratory rate is 24/min, SpO2 is 92% on room air, and temperature is 36.5\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a pulsatile and expansile mass in the midline. An urgent ultrasound confirms a ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of shock is most likely occurring in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypovolaemic shock","Cardiogenic shock","Obstructive shock","Distributive shock","Neurogenic shock"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing a ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm, which leads to massive internal bleeding into the retroperitoneal space. This results in a significant loss of blood volume, causing \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypovolaemic shock\u003C/strong\u003E. The clinical presentation of hypotension, tachycardia, and pallor is consistent with this type of shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the heart\u0027s inability to pump effectively, often due to myocardial infarction or severe heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstructive shock\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is a physical obstruction to blood flow, such as in pulmonary embolism or cardiac tamponade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistributive shock\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by widespread vasodilation, as seen in septic shock or anaphylaxis. The patient\u0027s symptoms and the presence of a ruptured aneurysm do not support this type of shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurogenic shock\u003C/strong\u003E results from a loss of sympathetic tone, often due to spinal cord injury, leading to hypotension and bradycardia. This is not applicable in this case, as the shock is due to blood loss from the aneurysm rupture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A ruptured aortic aneurysm typically leads to hypovolaemic shock due to massive internal bleeding.","Hypovolaemic shock is characterised by a significant loss of blood volume, leading to decreased cardiac output and tissue perfusion.","Early recognition and management of hypovolaemic shock are crucial to improve patient outcomes."],"references":["Roberts K, Revell M, Youssef H, Bradbury AW, Adam DJ. Hypotensive resuscitation in patients with ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm. Eur J Vasc Endovasc Surg. 2006 Apr;31(4):339-44. doi: 10.1016/j.ejvs.2005.11.003. Epub 2006 Jan 4. PMID: 16388972.","Gawenda M, Brunkwall J. Ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm: the state of play. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2012 Oct;109(43):727-32. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2012.0727. Epub 2012 Oct 26. PMID: 23181137; PMCID: PMC3498473.","Scali ST, Stone DH. Modern management of ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm. Front Cardiovasc Med. 2023 Dec 12;10:1323465. doi: 10.3389/fcvm.2023.1323465. PMID: 38149264; PMCID: PMC10749949.","Taghavi S, Nassar AK, Askari R. Hypovolemic Shock. 2023 Jun 5. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30020669."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60132"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17748"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60132"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T09:44:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T09:44:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10462"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74638"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rel